'''Indicator of compromise (IOC)''' — in [[computer forensics]] is an artifact observed on a [[computer network|network]] or in an [[operating system]] that with high confidence indicates a [[computer intrusion]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.rsa.com/understanding-indicators-of-compromise-ioc-part-i/ | title=Understanding Indicators of Compromise (IOC) Part I | publisher=RSA | year=2012 | accessdate=February 27, 2013}}</ref>
Typical IOCs are [[virus signature]]s and [[IP address]]es, [[MD5 hash]]es of [[malware]] files or [[URL]]s or [[domain name]]s of [[botnet]] command and control servers. After IOCs have been identified in a process of [[incident response]] and [[computer forensics]], they can be used for early detection of future attack attempts using [[intrusion detection system]]s and [[antivirus software]].
For more efficient automated processing there are initiatives to standardize the format of IOCs.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc5070.txt | title=The Incident Object Description Exchange Format | publisher=IETF | work=RFC 5070 | year=2007 | accessdate=February 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://cybox.mitre.org/ | title=Cyber Observable eXpression (CybOX) | publisher=Mitre | accessdate=February 27, 2013}}</ref> Known indicators are usually exchanged within the industry.{{cn|date=October 2017}}
