{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox book | name = Shopped | image = Joanna Blythman Shopped front cover.jpg | caption = Front cover of ''Shopped'' | author = [[Joanna Blythman]] | country = United Kingdom | language = English | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = [[HarperCollins|Fourth Estate]] | release_date = 4 May 2004 | media_type = Print (hardcover & paperback) | pages = 384 (first edition) | isbn = 978-0-00-715803-4 | oclc = 56444289 | followed_by = [[Joanna Blythman|Bad Food Britain]] }} '''''Shopped: The Shocking Power Of British Supermarkets''''' is a book by British author and [[Investigative journalism|investigative journalist]] [[Joanna Blythman]] first published by [[HarperCollins|Fourth Estate]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|title=What's so super about this? Poor meat, worse fish, flavourless vegetables|last=Jardine|first=Cassandra|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=30 April 2004|page=21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Books|last=Thinniswood|first=Rachel|work=[[Liverpool Echo]]|location=Liverpool|date=1 May 2004|page=25}}</ref><ref name="Blackmore">{{Cite news|title=Tesco consultation days in Sherborne|work=Blackmore Vale Magazine|location=Sturminster Newton|date=1 February 2013|page=8}}</ref> Described by one reviewer as "an emotive and bitter attack on [Britain's] supermarket culture" the book examines the way supermarkets have changed "diets, cities, countryside and economy" in Britain and argues that consumers have unwittingly "surrendered control over what [they] eat to a few powerful chains."<ref>{{Cite news|title=Food & Evil|last=Allan|first=Vicky|work=[[Sunday Herald]]|location=Glasgow|date=2 May 2004|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=The next 12 months promises to bring a revolution in the way we work, rest and play|first=Jim|last=McClellan|work=[[The Observer]]|location=London|date=28 December 2003|page=20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=How Tesco makes its millions|last=Prince|first=Dominic|work=[[The Spectator]]|location=London|volume=295|issue=9175|date=12 June 2004|pages=30–31}}</ref> Along with Felicity Lawrence's ''Not On The Label'' (2004) and [[Colin Tudge]]'s ''So Shall We Reap'' (2003), ''Shopped'' was seen by some critics as representing the frontline of the emerging, radical [[Slow Food]] movement in Europe.<ref>{{Cite news|title=The books of the year|first=David|last=Greig|authorlink=David Greig (dramatist)|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|location=Glasgow|date=4 December 2004|page=1}}</ref> The book helped establish Blythman's reputation as "one of the most influential commentators" on British supermarkets.<ref name=Blackmore/> It was the winner of the Best Food Book prize at the 2005 [[Glenfiddich Food and Drink Awards]] and was shortlisted for the 2005 [[Guild of Food Writers|Guild of Food Writers' Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Food writer honoured|work=[[Sunday Herald]]|location=Glasgow|date=22 May 2005|page=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Glenfiddich dishes out food awards|last=Simpson|first=Cameron|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|location=Glasgow|date=11 May 2005|page=8}}</ref>
